name: Snake Drop (Dinosaur)
description:
Snake Drop, named for a pictograph seen near the mouth of the canyon, contains several good downclimbs, nice sandstone narrows and a notable final rappel chamber. However, the approach is long and the off-trail return is long.

Similar to other canyons in the area, the canyon approach and return takes away from a better canyon rating, and leaves it not a destination canyon nor on the repeat list.

Approach

Set an optional shuttle vehicle along Highway 40 avoiding the private land.

Drive north on Harper's Corner Rd for 5.9 miles, just beyond Plug Hat Mesa. Turn right off pavement down Echo Park Rd into BLM land and a bumpy dirt two-track heading East. Reconsider this dirt road in rainy conditions or after recent precipitation. Park in an open field by a cattle pond.

Hike southwest on cattle trails on top of the mesa, avoiding private land and aiming for the start of the target drainage with GPS.

Descent

R1: 75' from a tree on Canyon Right

R2: 45' from a tree on Canyon Right

DC 20' with pool

An Emergency Exit potentially exists in a drainage on Canyon Right a few downclimbs after R2.

R3: 45' from a tree on Canyon Right

R4: 155' final rappel chamber from a wedged log in the streamcourse near the lip

DC 20' just below the final rappel

Exit

Return to the vehicle parked above: Proceed down canyon 850 feet and turn uphill on Canyon Right, climbing the hillside to reach the ridge top.

Heading North, try a path staying lower than the ridge and trending west of the emergency exit saddle to intersect a path up to the right (east) of a prominent butte seen on the approach.

Stay below the butte sandstone and the few short ridge sections that follow until they are continuous.

Continue uphill to the vehicle.

The return stats for Snake Drop refer to the uphill climb back and not to a shuttle.

If a shuttle vehicle is used, continue downstream avoiding private property to the car parked on Highway 40.

{{{caption}}}

Red tape

This write-up is a top down approach and uphill return. Parking below, closer to Highway 40 for a bottom up approach, is not possible on private land.
